I.	Software Requirement Specification
1. Product Overview
Upgrade the FPT Capture The Flag System is a project focused on upgrading and overcoming the existing limitations in the FCTF platform - the system serving the annual FPTU Secathon competition for information security students at FPT University. The upgraded version aims to improve the stability, security, performance, and operability of the system. The system provides a centralized environment for contestants to participate in solving security challenges, submitting flags, tracking results, and experiencing practical attack-defense scenarios in a controlled and safe environment.
 
Figure I 1: Context Diagram
The system includes four roles as described in Figure 1: Admin, Contestant, Jury, and Challenge Writer. Admin is the role with the highest authority, responsible for administering the entire system, including system configuration, creating, updating and managing user accounts, managing contests and challenges, handling tickets, and monitoring statistics and scoreboards. Contestant is the direct participant in the contests, able to view the challenge list, start or stop the contest environment, submit flags, open hints, send support tickets, and track contest results through the scoreboard. Jury acts as an observer to ensure the fairness and transparency of the contest, with the right to monitor team information, users, submissions, scoreboards, and overall system statistics. Challenge Writer is responsible for building, updating, and deploying challenges, while tracking deployment results to ensure the quality and stability of challenges in the system. 
The system has been deployed in three previous phases; therefore, in Phase 4, the team focuses on describing new functional and non-functional requirements or changes compared to the previous phases. Requirements that have been presented and remain unchanged will not be restated in this report. For a complete overview of the system's existing requirements, readers can refer to the report of the SEP490_G152 - Fall 2025 team.
2. User Requirements
2.1. User stories
2.1.1. Admin
As the person responsible for administering and monitoring the platform, including system configuration, user management, resource allocation, and ensuring stable system operation during the contest, I, as an Admin, want the system to provide the following functions:
●	US-01: As an Admin, I want the system to provide support functions such as search, pagination, filtering, and sorting of user and team information, dashboards, and logs, to manage contest data efficiently, with a clear interface capable of handling large amounts of data so I can identify important information when needed.
●	US-02: As an Admin, I want to be able to import and export contest data, lists of candidate and team information to a specific format and extract original passwords to quickly send login information to candidates, saving time for manual support.
●	US-03: As an Admin, I want to configure challenge deployment parameters such as CPU limits, memory, and timeout for workflows to control resources and ensure the infrastructure is not overloaded.
●	US-04: As an Admin, I want my system to thoroughly resolve race condition issues when contestants send requests to create environments, or send too many flag submission requests exceeding the allowed limit for each team.
●	US-05: As an Admin, I want to view a Dashboard with in-depth analytical metrics for each challenge, along with a log function recording all important operations, to monitor the contest and ensure transparency.
●	US-06: As an Admin, I want to view the deployment history (instance history) of each challenge by team/user even after the instance has been deleted or its Time to live has expired, to analyze abnormal behaviors and evaluate infrastructure quality after the contest.
●	US-07: As an Admin, I want the system to operate stably when handling a large number of start challenge requests simultaneously, avoiding resource deadlocks and downtime throughout the contest.
●	US-08: As an Admin, I want to query and aggregate award data based on multiple criteria and export it to Excel/CSV, in order to announce results accurately and transparently without manual operations.
2.1.2. Challenge Writer
As the person responsible for designing, building, and ensuring the quality of information security challenges in the system, I, as a Challenge Writer, want the system to provide the following functions:
●	US-09: As a Challenge Writer, I want to view, create, edit, and delete challenges in the system, and manage challenge versions so that I can rollback at any time, in order to maintain a high-quality challenge library for the contest.
●	US-10: As a Challenge Writer, I want to preview and test challenges in an isolated environment before official release, confirming that the connection string is only returned when the service inside the container is truly ready to receive requests, to ensure the quality of the contestant's experience from the first access.
●	US-11: As a Challenge Writer, I want to view the deployment history and real-time logs of challenge instances, to analyze and troubleshoot configuration issues - especially problems related to slow startup times or connection errors when contestants access them.
2.1.3. Jury
As the department responsible for monitoring the organization and competition process, ensuring the fairness, transparency, and integrity of the contests, as well as evaluating the results and behavior of contestants when necessary, I, as a Jury, want the system to provide the following functional and non-functional characteristics:
●	US-12: US-12: As a Jury, I want to view a Dashboard with detailed analytical metrics by each challenge and a real-time scoreboard, to monitor the contest progress and detect early signs of anomalies.
●	US-13: As a Jury, I want to view detailed information of users, teams, and submission history – filterable by team, user, and time period – to quickly investigate violations or cheating behaviors in the contest.
2.1.4. Contestant
As the direct participants in solving the challenges in the contest and the group interacting with the system most frequently, I, as a Contestant, want the system to provide the following functions:
●	US-14: As a Contestant, I want to initiate the challenge environment and only receive the connection string when the service inside the container is truly ready to accept connections so as not to encounter Connection Refused errors.
●	US-15: As a Contestant, I want to submit flags and receive validation results immediately, without encountering errors due to race conditions when multiple team members submit at the same time or send too many requests exceeding the limit, to accurately record points for the team in the contest.
●	US-16: As a Contestant, I want to view the scoreboard with a data refresh function to update the latest data in a timely manner.
●	US-17: As a Contestant, I want the system to have an intuitive and user-friendly interface; the test list, buttons, and notifications must be clear and easy to use, so that I don't spend too much time getting used to the system and can spend that time solving tests and achieving higher scores.
#	Actor	Description
1	Admin	Admin is responsible for administering the entire system and operating the F-CTF platform. This role performs system configuration at the global level, manages user accounts, assigns access permissions, and monitors resources to ensure stable system operation when hosting multiple contests simultaneously. Admin has the right to create, edit, or delete users, intervene in all resources in the system, handle support tickets, monitor scoreboards, aggregate statistics, and post-contest reports.
2	Challenge Writer
	Challenge Writer is responsible for designing, building, and managing challenge content in the system. This role can create, edit, and deploy challenges in the system. Challenge Writer monitors deployment history, checks logs and deploy results to ensure the quality, accuracy, and stability of challenges before they are used in contests.
3	Jury	Jury is the contest monitoring department to ensure the fairness, transparency, and integrity of the competition process. Jury has the right to view user information, participating teams, submissions, scoreboards, and aggregated statistics of the system. In addition, Jury can monitor logs, handle violation situations, respond to tickets when necessary, and support the evaluation and aggregation of final contest results.
4	Contestant	Contestants are those who directly participate in contests and solve challenges. They log in with granted accounts, update profile information, and participate in the contest. During the competition, Contestants can view the challenge list, start or stop the challenge environment, submit flags to record scores, track progress and the scoreboard. In addition, Contestants can send support tickets to the organizers and practice individually or as a team depending on the configuration.
