3.2. Manage Feature
3.2.1. FR-01: Challenge Gateway for Start Challenge
 
Figure 16: Challenge Gateway for Start Challenge Screen
In the current system, challenge pods used to be exposed directly to the outside environment using NodePort. Because NodePorts are located in a fixed and unchanging port range, contestants could guess or scan ports to gain unauthorized access to other teams' challenge instances, raising the risk of interference and sabotage to the competition environment. Therefore, the system implements a Challenge Gateway as a single intermediary layer that receives all requests from contestants, exposing only one fixed port and routing the request to the correct corresponding pod based on identity information.
The Challenge Gateway function is activated when a contestant performs the Start Challenge operation. Instead of returning a NodePort address directly, the system provides an access URL through the Gateway along with an authentication token. This token contains the necessary information for identification (user/team, challenge, internal port/route) to help the Gateway authenticate access rights and route the request to the correct instance. This approach enhances access control, reduces the attack surface, and keeps the contestant's experience consistent (accessing through only a single endpoint).

3.2.2. FR-02: Manage Challenges
 
Figure 66: View Challenges Screen
In the current system, administrators face many difficulties in managing challenges. When the contest scale is large, having to manually aggregate or extract the challenge list based on conditions is time-consuming and prone to errors. Therefore, the system improves the Challenges list screen to fully support browsing data and combined filtering/searching. The Search Challenge function is integrated directly at the top of the Challenges page and is used by Challenge Writers/Admins to quickly search and filter by multiple criteria. Users can combine the All Category dropdown, All Types dropdown (standard/dynamic/multiple_choice), Name dropdown (selecting search fields such as Name/Category/Type), Search keywords input, and filters for tags (displaying labels of selected tags and supporting tag search by name), difficulty, state (visible/hidden), and Has Prerequisite. After setting the conditions, the user clicks the Search button to apply or the Reset button to return the fields to their default state. The filtering/search results are displayed in a tabular list and accurately reflect the challenge data in the system.
3.2.3. FR-03: Configure deployment for Challenge
 
Figure 30: Configure deployment for Challenge Screen
When the user selects the “Docker Deploy” checkbox, the system displays a data entry form to configure the deployment. In the previous system, the configuration data only included the Expose port and deploy file, lacking settings regarding the memory and CPU resource requests of the pod. To resolve this issue and create a better control experience for the admin and challenge writer, the system adds inputs allowing users to customize settings: configuring CPU/Memory Request and Limit, enabling/disabling gVisor (Run the pod with gVisor sandbox for extra isolation), and Max Deploy Count (Maximum number of times a contestant can start/deploy this challenge)
3.2.4. FR-04: Edit dynamic challenge

 
Figure 30: Edit dynamic challenge Screen
The current system does not support the dynamic challenge type, where the score a contestant receives will decrease based on the number of correct submissions in the system. The necessary dynamic challenge customization interface includes: current value, initial value, Decay Function (Linear/Logarithmic), decay value, and minimum value. This function allows customization of the score the contestant receives, the type of function calculating the point reduction, and the minimum score the challenge can be reduced to.
3.2.5. FR-05: Challenge versions

 
Figure 30: Challenge versions Screen
In the current system, when a Challenge Writer edits a challenge (Dockerfile, flag, resources, description content), the change can be applied immediately without saving the history. If an update causes an error or breaks the deployment process, the challenge creator lacks the tools to trace back and revert to a stable state, leading to the risk of contest disruption. Therefore, the system adds a version control mechanism for challenges to record all changes over time.
The Challenge versions function allows Challenge Writers and Admins to access the Version History of a challenge to view the list of versions in chronological order. The interface is presented as a table with information including: version number, creation time, image tag, and active status. When viewing the details of a version, the user can review the attributes at that specific time, such as Docker configuration, flag, Resource Request/Limit, description content, and related settings. The version information helps users compare and evaluate the impact of each change, serving rollback purposes when needed.
3.2.6. FR-06: Rollback challenge version
 
Figure 30: Rollback challenge version Screen
Rollback challenge version is a direct complementary function to 3.2.2. FR-05, allowing a quick restoration to a stable version when the current version encounters a build/deploy error or causes issues during the contest. In the old system, restoration often had to be done manually (re-editing files, configurations, redeploying), which was time-consuming and error-prone. Therefore, the system provides a consistent Rollback operation on the Version History.
The user (Challenge Writer/Admin) selects a version from the version list and confirms the rollback via a popup to limit mistaken operations. After confirmation, the system restores the entire challenge configuration according to the selected version (Deploy file, resource limits/requests, description content, and related settings), then automatically triggers the rebuild and redeploy process via Argo Workflow.
3.2.7. FR-07: Refresh Log for Log Detail & Request Log
 
Figure 30: Refresh Log for Log Detail Screen
The challenge pod log viewing page in the previous system did not support real-time updates; users had to reload the entire page to see new content, disrupting the monitoring process and reducing the ability to react quickly when incidents occurred during deployment or during the competition. Thus, the system is supplemented with a refresh mechanism to update log content without reloading the entire page.
Admin can access the Log Detail page by clicking the [Logs] button corresponding to an instance on the Monitoring page. This page displays the general information section (challenge id) and the text-based log content area. Users can click [Refresh] to load the latest content without reloading the page, or use the auto-refresh function to automatically update after a period of time; the system simultaneously displays the latest update time to ensure trackability.
 
Figure 30: Contestant Request Log Screen
