4.4. Flow Assessment
After completing the analysis of critical trust boundaries related to key infrastructure components and assets (such as the Kubernetes API Server, Argo Workflows, MariaDB, and Redis), the system model continues with an evaluation from a business flow perspective to reflect realistic attack scenarios.
Analyzing trust boundaries provides a structured view of important communication points. However, internal service interactions are not analyzed in isolation; they are abstracted and evaluated through business flows, since real risk only manifests when these interactions are part of a complete end-to-end process.
In this section, each flow represents a full end-to-end interaction, starting from an entry point and passing through multiple system components. This approach allows the identification of attack paths across services, as well as scenarios for privilege escalation and business logic abuse.
Threats within each flow are classified according to the STRIDE model and assessed based on predefined risk criteria.
The system is analyzed across four critical business flows, covering interactions from both users and administrative or operational processes:
●	Flow 1: Contestant Start Challenge 
●	Flow 2: Admin Create Challenge 
●	Flow 3: Contestant Submit Flag
●	Flow 4: Contestant Access Challenge via Gateway
